==Chinese==
{{zh-forms|alt=匞}}

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
Traditionally thought to be an {{Han compound|匚|斤|ls=ic|t1=box|t2=axe|nocap=1}} (e.g. ''{{w|Shuowen}}'').

In more recent scholarship (e.g. {{zh-ref|Zhengzhang, 2003}}; {{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart, 2014}}), an alternative glyph origin has been proposed, suggesting that it is a {{Han compound|匚|斤|ls=psc|c1=p|c2=s|t2=axe|nocap=1}}.

===Etymology===
Several etymologies have been proposed:
* Related to {{cog|bo|བྱང||skilled}} ({{zh-ref|Bodman, 1980}}) or {{m|bo|སྤྱང||skilful; clever}} ({{zh-ref|Sagart and Baxter, 2012}}). These comparisons would require the {{cog|och|-}} reconstruction to have a ''*sb-'' initial, which is possible if {{och-l|匚}} is considered to be the phonetic component. The Middle Chinese initial would be derived as such: ''*s.b-'' > ''*zb-'' > ''*bz-'' > ''*dz-'' ({{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart, 2014}}).
* {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}}, who reconstructs the {{cog|och|-}} minimally as ''*dzaŋh'', deems it more likely to be from {{der|zh|mkh}}, comparing it to {{cog|km|ចាំង||to dress; to trim (wood)}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).
* {{zh-ref|Jacques (2015)}} proposes another {{der|zh|sit}} etymology, comparing it to {{cog|bo|མཛངས||wise; intelligent}}, which is derived from {{m|bo|བཟང||good}}. Under this hypothesis, it can be derived from {{och-l|臧|tr=*[ts]ˤaŋ|good}}, which has been connected to the Tibetan word. He postulates the derivation to consist of the nominalizing circumfix ''*k- -s'' and the applicative prefix ''*N-'', yielding ''*k-N-tsaŋ-s'' > ''*k-dzaŋ-s''.

